metadata.name: Paper Mandala #296
metadata.description:
A collaboration with P1xelboy and Paper Buddha.
Beautiful paper mandalas made purely with code in Paper Buddha's style.
Features include:
27 different palettes
3 different mandala types (Lotus, Starburst Style 1 and Starburst Style 2)
Four sections of the mandala with one of 10 different pattern types (Dots, Checks, Crosses, Triangles, Stripes, Circles, Polygons, Lazers, Quadrants and Hatching)
4 different direction types of shadow - of varying length
Randomly placed star background
Randomly placed Nebula
Possible Special Pattern Effect with darker stippling pattern
Possible Nirvana Effect where random colors are added to one of either Golden, Silver, Bronze, Blue Moon or Sea Green palettes.

Using only code, this produces a unique output which does take a few seconds to load.
Press "S" to Save your unique Paper Mandala as a 2048 x 2048 JPG
Press "R" for a random shuffle effect - (please wait for reload) - Refresh page to reset

The project works in a responsive browser, so to set up for phone background or watch, resize the browser accordingly and Alt + Print Screen to get an appropriately sized image.

Offered as a Dutch Auction, holders of the first 20 tokens (1-20) will receive additional benefits in the form of utility for future releases in the P1xelboy/Paper Mandala collaboration series. (exact details to be determined)
This utility will remain attached to tokens 1-20 and transfer to the new owner upon subsequent secondary sales.

Uses p5.js and p5.pattern
@p1x3lboy @paperbuddha - September 2022

metadata.name: Traffic #228
metadata.description:
Traffic is a companion piece to Scaffold. Whilst Scaffold was intended to capture a moment in time of a single mind, Traffic aims to represent a shared moment in a community.

Outputs can be beautiful, but can also be chaotic. They can be comprised of many contributions, but a single voice may drown out many others.

All royalties go to the original minter.

Keyboard commands:

s - save as png
h - toggle high resolution 
b - toggle background texture
a - switch aspect ratio
r - new moment

metadata.name: High Spirits! #220
metadata.description:
There’s always a time and a place to let loose, sit back, and lift those spirits! Through the ages, images of the filled cup, mug, or cocktail glass have molded the way we envision relaxation and good times. They’ve encoded an escape, a panacea, a nostalgic refuge, and a feeling that we seek — but may not find. 

So instead, let’s stay in the moment and live sip by sip, here and now. Let’s look directly into the blazing neon lights, experience something unexpected, and remember that the best drink is one shared. Cheers to all!

--------

Many pieces of High Spirits! match the community-favorite cocktails shared in the Tender Discord’s #happyhour channel… others are timeless cocktails and mocktails, defined in bold headline. Still more outputs are generative mysteries, concocted from Mr. Kislev’s Kode, open to your inventive interpretations. Enjoy the eighties electric vibes and mid-century styling, print a poster, and trade for your favorites!

--------

TENDER x Orr Kislev
September 2022

metadata.name: Bored Computer Screen #795
metadata.description:
"Bored Computer Screen" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at Art Basel, Basel 2022


Bored Computer Screen (BCS) is a direct descendant of Specter👻pixel⬛latte☕, where the central idea is agent and displacement. In BCS, there are agents—the small moving circles—that get their colors ripped away by the surrounding pixels. Though they occur on the same screen space, they are separated in their own cells, a simultaneous multiverse of sorts. In some iterations, a very clear voronoi pattern will appear. I didn't consciously strive for this look. It's what naturally happens, when you try to divide space, so that the borders occur exactly in between the closest neighbor. When I first saw this pattern emerge, I wanted to see how far I could get the distinct cells to influence each other. The idea that the same algorithmic processes can happen many times but still separately in a single piece has always interested me (and explored in the Infinite Browse series). BCS is an extension of that, albeit a little more chaotic.

Note:
- Best experience on browsers and devices with support for WebGL2 

Made by Sam Tsao (@sam___tsao) with P5, P5Fbo and perlinjs.

metadata.name: Sixty# #13
metadata.description:
This idea was born from recent discussion on generative art and the path the medium is finding for itself. The project aims to take aesthetic concepts from sci fi graphic novels and blend them with generative systems of abstraction. 

The debate is between using previously established art forms to influence this new medium, or using a new medium to meticulously reproduce a previous medium. I believe there’s room to explore the full spectrum, and I am attempting to find the midpoint that fits my work and brings me the most happiness.

The title describes the eventual aesthetic objective, which is to create a piece which might look like a splash page a colorist alone has been given the freedom to design and explore their own specialty. It explores centralized polar compositions, vibrant colors, plus lots and lots of movement. 60# paper is a standard weight for printing of comic books and graphic novels.

Press ’s’ in live view to save a .png

Created with p5.js and chroma.js

metadata.name: Broken Symmetries #1/3 #35
metadata.description:
"It was the best of times, it was the worst of times, it was the age of wisdom, it was the age of foolishness, it was the epoch of belief, it was the epoch of incredulity, it was the season of Light, it was the season of Darkness, it was the spring of hope, it was the winter of despair, we had everything before us, we had nothing before us..."
                                      Charles Dickens

This piece is the first in a planed series of three intended as studies on composition.

It is built entirely on thi.ng/umbrella libraries and template:

https://github.com/thi-ng/fxhash-tpl

Keyboard shortcuts

- 1 : render @ original resolution
- 2 : render @ 2 x resolution
- 4 : render @ 4 x resolution
- x : download canvas as PNG @ current resolution
- s : download canvas as SVG @ current resolution; This can be used with a plotter.

metadata.name: Different Intersections - Iteration 4 #58
metadata.description:
This is the culmination of a series of iterations

____ - Iteration 1
____ - Iteration 2
____ - Iteration 3

The iterations were released under the pseudonym Extracurricular Activities.

The algorithmic theme of the iterations was extensive usage of boolean operations (intersection and difference) on polygons to derive interesting composite shapes.

In live mode, add &size=<YOUR_PIXEL_SIZE> to change the pixel size of the image for export (Right click to save). For example, &size=4000 will set the width of the image to be 4000 pixels.

metadata.name: Klyft #683
metadata.description:
“Klyft” is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at PARIS+ par Art Basel.

Klyft is a juxtaposition of two different projections for the future. One, made by the World Economic Forum, suggests that the global gender gap will have closed by the year 2154. The other, by the UN IPCC, estimates that global warming will reach 3.2 degrees celcius by the year 2100.

Klyft makes use of the unique temporal aspect of computational art by developing its expression gradually over the next 132 years. As we come closer to 2154, the space between the two shapes in Klyft will grow smaller to symbolize the closing of the gender gap. As time goes on, however, Klyft also becomes more and more glitched out to represent the projected increases in greenhouse gases and climate catastrophes.

In the end, Klyft’s expression will be heavily corrupted, and the two shapes will have reached each other.

· URL parameters ·

You can add the following parameters to the URL to change the behavior of the piece.

date=<YYYY-MM-DD> — See how Klyft looks on another day. Use the format YYYY-MM-DD. 

color=<number> — See the piece in another color scheme. The numbers loop around, so 17 equals 0, 18 equals 1, etc. 

resolution=<number> — View the piece in a higher resolution. 1 is normal resolution, 2 is double, etc. No decimals allowed.

image=true — Save the piece as an image. 

record=true — Save the piece as a video in WEBM format.

Adding the following URL parameters will show Klyft in double resolution on the day gender equality is achieved according to the WEF:

date=2154-01-01&resolution=2

Adding the following URL parameters will save a video of Klyft in the ‘Stokkendahl Dalgas’ color scheme:

color=14&record=true

· Interactions ·

Pressing the following keys will trigger functionality as well as add related URL parameters automatically. 

Pressing D will increment the date by 1 year.

Pressing C will increment the color index by 1.

Pressing R will toggle between normal and double resolution.

Pressing I will toggle the image URL parameter, which saves the piece as an image. Only works outside of iframe.

Pressing V will toggle the video URL parameter, which saves the piece as a video. Only works outside of iframe.

There are secret key presses as well. Some of them only work outside of iframe. 

· Accessibility ·

Klyft is built to support screen readers. It has been tested using MacOS’ VoiceOver, and uses p5.js’ describeElement() to provide screen reader functionality.

If you have any comments (good or bad) on the screen reader integration, don’t hesitate to reach out on my Twitter: @ada_ada_ada_art. 

· Credits and license ·

Klyft is made with p5.js.

Klyft is licensed under a modified version of the Climate Strike License (CSL).

metadata.name: Wanderer #259
metadata.description:
Wanderer is an algorithm which uses hexagonal Truchet tiles to produce meandering paths of color. Originally created back in February, I am releasing it as part of this week's #fxhashturnsone celebration.

100% of primary sales will go the the Processing foundation.

Thank you to fx(hash) and to the entire generative art community. 

CONTROLS:

For third party license information, please see license.md

David Brice Allen
November 2022

metadata.name: Ontologies #141
metadata.description:
A system designed to make art out of its own code. 

What is the 'artful' component of generative art - is it the algorithm's form or the aesthetics of individual outputs? Ontologies brings the code out of the shadows into the foreground, nudging the viewer to consider this system's recursive existence. 

Is there something vaguely mortal, or at least vulnerable, about a system 'aware' of its own inner workings (like a person contemplating their DNA code)? Our use of computers to express incomputable human inspiration and creativity suggests that we already see them as more than just tools or calculating machines. So who is the artist, and what is the art?

Made with p5.js

metadata.name: Slumbers #148
metadata.description:
Generative abstract artwork that explores forms, shapes, coloring and brushwork.

Options:

- press 'f' to turn off paper-like texture (recommended for print on hi-quality paper)
- press 's' to save the PNG image of the current view
- press 1, 2, 3, or 4 to save hi-res PNG images

Colors and textures might differ slightly on some devices due to the heavy use of low alpha blending. Calibrated and tested on Firefox 107.0 & Chrome 107.0.5304.107 on Win10 x64 Intel machine.

Created using p5js.

@VolatileMoods, November, 2022.

metadata.name: Prophecy #138
metadata.description:
Elder Futhark Runes / Proto-Germanic alphabets flowing through the canvas.

Each iteration gets a random rune from 24 runes and the vector field angles are based on that.

Also picks one word from what the random rune symbolizes as a prophecy for the next year.

Minted for #fxhashturnsone event 18.11.2022.

50% of primary profits to Processing Foundation.

Save image with 's'.

Load 2x or 4x dimensions (2560 * 3840px) image with '2' or '4'.
